<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Essex County Council (LTD0040)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Essex County Council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(LTD0040)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Essex County Council welcomes the Select Committee’s invitation to submit evidence on local decision making for transport schemes and would wish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the foll</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owing submission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he Rational</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The County Council sees the m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ove from a complex array of challenge funding, local block allocations and major scheme funding routes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as a positive move </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signaling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a new emphasis on local decision making rather than direct control by Central Government. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e newly implemented arrangement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s for LTB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funding and LEP SEP funding have already resulted in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a better basis for local investment priorities to be determined and advanced collectively with partners. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The advantages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of undertaking this work in the way being rolled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> include potentially</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> greater transparency of decision-making</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amongst stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, more involvement of partners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and stakeholders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in ensuring outcomes are achieved, less bureaucracy in carrying out multiple funding bids</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a pipeline of work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rather than the pursuit of one-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f opportunities for funding through challenge bids or major project applications.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Possible disadva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ntages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> include, less democratic accountability, devising compliant assurance frameworks, the involvement of multiple partners in the local decision making process, the gradual erosion of Local Transport Plans and a possible erosion of autonomy that the Local Tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nsport Authorities currently enjoy which carries with it statutory Highway Authority responsibilities.</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local t</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ransport boards) have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Count</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y Council does not see that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local bodies as being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">set up as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">separate delivery entities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; rather they are a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> collection of decision makers engaged upon a collective exercise in prioritizing work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is then implemented through existing mechanisms. If viewed in this way the capacity already in the system can be harnessed to add value to the process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> On occasio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n there may be the need for consultancy assistance but this would be targeted at specific tasks rather than being used on an ongoing basis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Within the SELTB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and SELEP the collective resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been harnessed to produce an a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssurance framework to satisfy Government and National Audit requirements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as well as an internal prioritisation process where benefits both transport and economic can be drawn together from the collective wisdom, perspective and knowledge of the parent org</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">anisations.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">An optimum body</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is difficult to specify. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> body set up needs to reflect the circumstances, geography, statutory powers, resourcing and partnerships which can be harnessed by those who form the driving force to plan and deliver transport impr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ovements. LTBs and LEPS vary across the country. Some conform to existing local authority boundaries, whilst others cover multiple authority areas. Furthermore prior to LTBs being devised government had the idea that perhaps consortia would become establis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hed, recognising perhaps that a consortium would cross boundaries in the pursuit of a single project or strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and presumably could be formed and then dissolved once the task or project had been achieved. The concept of Integrated Transport Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is open to Councils under statute </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and whereas the existing Passenger T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport Authorities have embraced this concept others areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">notic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ably in the south of the co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">untry)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have yet to take this approach.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the best way of dealing with major transport</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Traditionally these proposals often come through the auspices of HA or NR since their projects naturally effect more than one authority. Occasionally and increasingly local autho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rities take the lead such as the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> examples</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A14 promoted and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coordinated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Cambridgeshire County Council or the A47 by Norfolk County Council. What seems certain is that considerable engagement needs to take place outside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perhaps the traditional c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onsultation or even planning mechanisms which may present too much of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">formal “atmosphere” for useful dialogue to take place. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Essex use has been made of the Transport Boar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ds which exist in Thames Gateway, Haven Gateway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the London-Stansted Gateway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Here multiple authority-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> organisations, businesses and other agencies have the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">part of a strategic approach which then spawns major projects. The collective input helps to raise awareness for the promoting authority and the project itse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lf gains wider support through this approach.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Boards are engagement mechanisms rather than delivery bodies and projects are implemented through partner organisation supply chains with their own internal governance used to ensure both project and democr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">atic accountability</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the LEP arena, current experience has shown a similar effect to the Transport Boards. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Once the first generation of SEPs has been produced there will be a need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cross-LEP discussions on the larger projects. Such discussion for a ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve yet to emerge to consider specific projects although they are in evidence to take on board the influences of ideas and programmes being advanced by neighbouring LEPs.</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments a</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nd national transport agencies?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It has been Essex’s experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that cross-authority, cross-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LEP and joint working with HA and NR has resulted in good working arrangements which foster a collaborative approach. The experience of the Transport Boards has demo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nstrated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> collaboration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> HA in particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and with DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> generally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been extremely helpful. Improvements how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ver need to be made and the areas below are possible candidates for this:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HA as it becomes a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Corporation, because the planning of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its workload will take on a more business-like approach perhaps similar to that of N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etwork </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new approach will need to ensure that the recent moves to approach the planning of its networks through recognition of the importance of local economic geo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">graphies is continued. There must be an over-riding “duty to co-operate” such that the overlapping timetables of work between HA and the planning and transport authorities do not cause unnecessary tension</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etwork </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: the highly segmented approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">used by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> NR is complex and often impenetrable. Many opportunities exist to collaborate and whilst these often result in excellent joint working there must be more work done to establish engagement mechanisms especially with local planning and transport authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on common areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as the interface with highway and public transport networks at stations etc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Semi-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">autonomous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> agencies such as the HCA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have an increasing role to play with engagement with the new bodies as they can re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dily assist with both transport a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd accessing land for new economic or growth opportunities.</span></li></ul><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do the current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current funding being m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ade available for major projects is greater than that made available in previous comprehensive spending reviews. Although it was disappointing to see the initial allocation reduced with the onset of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LTB/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SEP, there are signs that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all-in-all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local Transp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ort Authorities will see on average more than the one major scheme per five year average that was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inherent in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the previous system. In part this is a function of the extra funding being made available and in part this is because six years of funding has bee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n outlined leading to greater confidence that it is worth the investment in upfront design and planning work prior to impleme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tation.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Within this generally favorable landscape however there are some areas which cause local transport authorities genuine </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concern:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The partial loss of the IT block and the potential for smaller scheme implementation to diminish given the natural desire for SEP infrastructure to focus on larger schemes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The inability to bid for and attract funding for the wholesale renewal of s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ignificant assets. An example in Essex is the A127which as a former trunk road is beyond the ability of the County Council to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">renew now that the route is approaching 80 years since its pavement formation was first created. Whilst it is true that such proje</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cts can be funded through the SEP, the scale involved with this work is considerable.</span></li></ul><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What impact will the devolution in 2015 of funding to Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the Single Local Growth Fund have?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The impacts foreseen are largely p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ositive and comprise: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">swifter arrangements for planning, design and delivery of transport schemes because of the ability to determine these locally without the need to submit complex business cases and challenge bids to central Governmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t and await their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">determination</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more joined up thinking between businesses, private sector organisations and planning authorities with transport proposals</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategic planning rather than one-off initiatives</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">encouraging a pipeline of projects to assist programme management</span></li></ul><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ho</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">w can local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most authorities make extensive use of s106 </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and t</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he move to CIL will enable transport infrastructure to support growing communities to continue</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The timetable for CIL is slow to emerge however</span></li><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alternative funding sources such as the use of Business Rates, New Homes Bonus, PFI are all possible future </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">routes as traditional sources come under greater pressure</span></li><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Direct investment by pension funds or the imaginative use of asset backed vehicles are other possible routes for longer term investment.</span></li></ul><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">making on transport expenditure?</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In most areas there is an established Highway authority or an ITA or a PTA. These are organisations with democratically elected members with clear lines of accountable. Where agency arrangements exist there may be some conf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usion in the minds of the public however as long as it is clear who to contact about specific matters then such confusion can be managed. Most authorities publish their expenditure plans through their budget setting processes, their periodic LTPs and most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">make their funding bids to government available for public access. In Essex we have taken a localism approach to many of our minor schemes with Local Highways Panels being set up across Essex District Localities where prioritisation and decision making tak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e place increasingly in public.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For trunk roads and rail systems the lines of accountability are sometimes less obvious. Geographic areas of responsibility do not conform to Council boundaries and there are contracted out aspects of maintenance and scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">delivery.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 82.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the move to LTBs and LEPs there is presently these are no consistent approach across the country and the system is evolving making much of its business publically accessible but it will take time to understand the new responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rawing together of business, planning and highway authorities is very helpful to the process of understanding the merit of individual proposals but it is not yet clear where the accountability lies for decision making.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>